=begin pod

=head1 02. Your First Schema

In Slangify, the schema is a Raku Grammar. Each named token is a field; the
C<TOP> rule defines the canonical DSL line the LLM must produce.

=head2 The booking grammar

=begin code :lang<raku>
grammar Slangify::Tutorial::Grammar {
    token TOP {
        <.ws>
        name        <.ws> <name>       <.ws>
        party       <.ws> <party>      <.ws>
        time        <.ws> <time>       <.ws>
        restaurant  <.ws> <restaurant> <.ws>
        date        <.ws> <date>       <.ws>?
        $
    }

    token name       { '"' <( <-["]>+ )> '"' }
    token party      { \d+                   }
    token time       { \d+ ':' \d\d          }
    token restaurant { '"' <( <-["]>+ )> '"' }
    token date       { \S+                   }
    token ws         { \h*                   }
}
=end code

=head2 Field types

=defn name / restaurant
Quoted string — any characters except C<">. The C<< <( )> >> markers strip
the surrounding quotes from the capture.

=defn party
One or more digits — coerced to C<Int> by the C<Booking> class.

=defn time
24-hour C<HH:MM> — e.g. C<19:30> for 7:30 pm.

=defn date
Any non-whitespace token: C<today>, C<tomorrow>, a weekday, or C<2026-06-01>.

=head2 Required vs optional

Every field in C<TOP> is required by default. To make a field optional, add
C<**{0..1}> or C<?>  after its subrule call, and handle the missing case in
C<Booking>.

=head2 Testing the grammar standalone

The grammar parses the canonical DSL line without any LLM, keeping the schema that defines your DSL distinct and concrete to maximize clarity, effectiveness and ease of test:

=begin code :lang<raku>
my $m = Slangify::Tutorial::Grammar.parse(
    'name "Jane" party 4 time 19:30 restaurant "Bistro Verde" date tomorrow'
);
say $m<name>;        # Jane
say $m<party>;       # 4
say $m<restaurant>;  # Bistro Verde
=end code

=end pod
